Boil a full #kettle{}.

Pour the @boiled water for the sauce{100%ml} into a #measuring jug{}.

Pour the remaining @water{} into a #medium saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring back to the boil. Add the @egg noodle nest{125%g} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%mins}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine the @peanut butter{30%g}, @soy sauce{15%ml}, @ketjap manis{25%g}, @sugar{1.5%tsp} and boiled water for the sauce.

Stir until well combined.

> TIP: If your peanut butter has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Next, cut the @Tenderstem® broccoli{150%g} into thirds. Halve any thick broccoli stems lengthways.

Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #large frying pan{} on high heat. Drain the @king prawns{150%g}.

Once hot, add the prawns, broccoli and sliced pepper and stir-fry until the prawns cook through, ~{4-5%mins}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

While the prawns cook through, cut the @lime{1} into wedges. Crush the @salted peanuts{25%g} in the unopened sachet using a #rolling pin{}.

When the veg has softened, lower the heat to medium.

Stir in the @yellow Thai style paste{45%g} and @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} to the pan. Cook until fragrant, ~{1%min}.

Stir through the peanut butter mixture and simmer until slightly reduced, ~{2-3%mins}.

Add the cooked noodles to the pan and toss to coat in the sauce, ~{1-2%mins}.

Squeeze in half the lime juice, then remove from the heat.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if you feel it needs it.

Taste, and add more salt, pepper or lime juice if needed.

Share the yellow Thai style prawn noodles between your serving bowls.

Sprinkle over the peanuts.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges to finish. Enjoy!